## Bug Report
### Expected behavior
When I'm renewing an expired license, the item price label should read "license renewal".

### Actual behavior
It reads "license upgrade".

### Steps to reproduce the behavior
1) Set up a bundled download with price variations.
2) Register a customer user and, with that user, buy the bundle.
3) As the shop admin, set the license's expiry date to a date in the past, making it expired.
4) As the customer, follow the process to renew the license. On the cart, check the label next to the item's price.

### Information (if a specific version is affected):
EDD Version (or branch):  3.2.3

### Proposal for solution
Note that I delimited the changes I suggest with `// CODE ADDED START/END`

edd-software-licensing/includes/license-upgrades.php
```php
/**
 * @since 3.3
 * @param $price float The current item price
 * @param $download_id int Download product ID
 * @param $options array the cart item options
 * @return float
 */
function edd_sl_license_upgrade_cart_item_price_label( $label, $download_id, $options ) {
	global $edd_sl_cart_item_quantity_removed;

	if( empty( $options['is_upgrade'] ) || ! isset( $options['upgrade_id'] ) ) {
		return $label;
	}

	$edd_sl_cart_item_quantity_removed = true;
	add_filter( 'edd_item_quantities_enabled', '__return_false' );

	// CODE ADDED START
	if ( isset( $options['is_renewal'] ) && true === $options['is_renewal'] ) {
		return $label . ' - ' . __( '<em>license renewal</em>', 'edd_sl' );
	}
	// CODE ADDED END

	return $label . ' - ' . __( '<em>license upgrade</em>', 'edd_sl' );
}
add_filter( 'edd_cart_item_price_label', 'edd_sl_license_upgrade_cart_item_price_label', 10, 3 );
```

## Bug Report

*NOTE: this refers to edd-software-licensing plugin*

### Expected behavior
Let's consider 2 bundle products and a download with price variations. Both bundles include that download, but with different price assignments. To make the example more specific, let's consider:
- A "Basic" bundle that includes the "Download" at price "Basic Price".
- A "Pro" bundle that includes the "Download" at price "Pro Price".

When the user buys either a "Basic" or "Pro" bundle, he receives a *parent* license for the bundle with a *child* license for the "Download".

When the customer upgrades his "Basic" license to "Pro", we expect the *parent* license to be updated and the *child* license to remain associated with it.

### Actual behavior
In the scenario described above, the *child* license is being removed.

When upgrading a license, EDD checks whether the downloads in the new bundle are also part of the old bundle. For those that aren't, it creates a new license for them. And those that were part of the old bundle and are not in the new bundle are removed.

The issue seems to be that EDD checks this in two different places, `EDD_SL_License➝create()` and `edd_sl_get_license_upgrades()`, and does it differently in both. In the former, it checks only the product ID whereas in the latter it checks the product ID and price ID.

When the old and new bundles contain the same download but at different price assignments, the *child* license for that download is removed.

### Steps to reproduce the behavior
1) Set up 2 bundles and a download with variable price, as described above.
2) Register a customer user and, with that user, buy the "Basic" bundle.
3) As the shop admin, go to the Licenses admin table (at `/wp-admin/edit.php?post_type=download&page=edd-licenses`) and check the existence of the parent and child licenses.
3) As the customer, upgrade to the "Pro" bundle.
4) As the shop admin, go again to the Licenses admin table and see that the parent has been updated, but the child is missing.

### Information (if a specific version is affected):
EDD Version (or branch): 3.2.3

WordPress Version: 6.3.1

Any other relevant information:

### Proposal for solution
Check for download and price separately, not comparing download ID (e.g. `1000`) with download with product ID (e.g. `1000_10`).

Note that I delimited the changes I suggest with `// CODE CHANGES START/END`

*edd-software-licensing/includes/license-upgrades.php*
```php
/**
 * Process the license upgrade during purchase
 *
 * @since 3.3
 * @return void
 */
function edd_sl_process_license_upgrade( $download_id = 0, $payment_id = 0, $type = 'default', $cart_item = array(), $cart_index = 0 ) {
		// Code here...

		$license->create( $download_id, $payment_id, $price_id, $cart_index, $options );

		if ( $new_download->licensing_enabled() ) {
			// Now that we've created all necessary new child licenses, remove any keys that don't belong in this

			// CODE CHANGES START
			$child_licenses = $license->get_child_licenses();
			foreach ( $child_licenses as $child_license ) {
				$child_d_in_new_downloads = false;

				foreach ( $new_bundle_downloads as $new_d_id ) {
					$new_d_id_parts = array_map( 'intval', explode( '_', $new_d_id ) );

					if ( $child_license->download_id === $new_d_id_parts[0] ) {
						$child_d_in_new_downloads = true;

						if ( isset( $new_d_id_parts[1] ) && $child_license->price_id !== $new_d_id_parts[1] ) {
							$child_license->update(
								array(
									'price_id' => $new_d_id_parts[1],
								)
							);
						}
						break;
					}
				}

				if ( ! $child_d_in_new_downloads ) {
					$child_license->delete();
				}
			}
			// CODE CHANGES END
		}

		// Code here...
}
```

## Bug Report

*NOTE: this refers to edd-software-licensing plugin*

### Expected behavior
Let's consider a bundled download with price variations. When the license for this bundle is expired, the user should be able to renew the license by re-purchasing the product at the same price. We use `edd_sl_get_license_upgrades()` to display the available purchasing options to the user.

### Actual behavior
The list returned by `edd_sl_get_license_upgrades()` excludes the same product at the same price (even though `edd_sl_get_upgrade_paths()` includes it) because of the fact that the price is the same. Therefore, we're only showing options to _upgrade_ the product, and not also to _renew_ the same product.

### Steps to reproduce the behavior
1) Set up a bundled download with price variations.
2) Register a customer user and, with that user, buy the bundle.
3) Set the license's expiry date to a date in the past, making it expired.
4) Go to a page that calls `edd_sl_get_license_upgrades()` and see if the options include that same bundle at the same price it was bought..

### Information (if a specific version is affected):
EDD Version (or branch): 3.2.3

WordPress Version: 6.3.1

### Proposal for solution
Check if the license is expired with `$license->is_expired()`. If it is, then don't remove the renewal "upgrade path" from the list of options, regardless of the price.

Note that I delimited the changes I suggest with `// CODE CHANGES START/END`

*edd-software-licensing/includes/license-upgrades.php*
```php
/**
 * Retrieve the possible upgrades for a license
 *
 * @since 3.3
 * @return array
 */
function edd_sl_get_license_upgrades( $license_id = 0 ) {
		// Code here...

		if ( $status_is_upgradable ) {
			$upgrade_paths = edd_sl_get_upgrade_paths( $license->download_id );
		}

		if ( ! empty( $upgrade_paths ) && is_array( $upgrade_paths ) ) {

			foreach ( $upgrade_paths as $key => $path ) {

				if ( $license->get_download()->has_variable_prices() ) {

					// If there is a different product in the upgrade paths, upgrade is available
					if ( (int) $path['download_id'] === (int) $license->download_id ) {

						// CODE CHANGES START
						if ( $license->is_expired() ) {
							continue;
						}
						// CODE CHANGES END

						// If same download but with a more expensive price ID is in upgrade paths, upgrade is available
						if ( (int) $path['price_id'] !== (int) $license->price_id ) {

							if ( edd_get_price_option_amount( $path['download_id'], $path['price_id'] ) <= edd_get_price_option_amount( $license->download_id, $license->price_id ) ) {
								unset( $upgrade_paths[ $key ] );
							}
						} else {

							if ( edd_get_price_option_amount( $path['download_id'], $path['price_id'] ) <= edd_get_price_option_amount( $license->download_id, $license->price_id ) ) {
								unset( $upgrade_paths[ $key ] );
							}
						}
					}
				} else {

					// If there is a different product in the upgrade paths, upgrade is available
					if ( (int) $path['download_id'] === (int) $license->download_id ) {
						unset( $upgrade_paths[ $key ] );
					}
				}
			}
		}
	}

	return apply_filters( 'edd_sl_get_license_upgrade_paths', $upgrade_paths, $license_id );
}
```

## Bug Report
### Expected behavior
The `$cart_details` array passed to functions that hook into `edd_complete_download_purchase` (an action done in `edd_complete_purchase()`) should have all of its values unserialized. A few of its values aren't, though. 

This is happening because `edd_get_order_item_meta()` is called without defining a metakey. When a metakey is not set in `get_metadata()` (which is called by `edd_get_order_item_meta()`), WordPress doesn't unserialize the data (see [last portion of `get_metadata_raw()`](https://github.com/WordPress/wordpress-develop/blob/trunk/src/wp-includes/meta.php#L656)).

### Actual behavior
The `$cart_details` array passed to functions hooked into `edd_complete_download_purchase` should be deeply unserialized.

### Steps to reproduce the behavior
1) Hook a function that outputs the value of `$cart_details` into `edd_complete_download_purchase` and see what's outputted. You can use the following output function:

```php
if ( ! function_exists( 'write_log' ) ) {
	function write_log( $log ) {
		if ( is_array( $log ) || is_object( $log ) ) {
			error_log( print_r( $log, true ) );
		} else {
			error_log( $log );
		}
	}
}
```

### Information (if a specific version is affected):
EDD Version (or branch): 3.2.3

WordPress Version: 6.3.1

Any other relevant information:
Happens in the Pro plugin as well.
